<BaseLayout
  title="About - The National Signal"
  description="What The National Signal covers, how it approaches uncertainty, and what readers should expect."
>
  <article class="infoPage">
    <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
    <h1>Reporting the change before it becomes obvious</h1>
    <p class="infoLead">The National Signal is an independent digital publication focused on the early indicators behind consequential changes in technology, business, politics, culture, and the world.</p>

    <section>
      <h2>What we publish</h2>
      <p>We look for developments that are visible in primary records, credible reporting, public data, corporate activity, regulation, infrastructure, and institutional behavior. Our goal is to explain what has changed, what is known, what remains uncertain, and what readers should watch next.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What a signal is</h2>
      <p>A signal is an observable development that may point toward a larger shift. It is not proof of a prediction. We distinguish verified facts from analysis and avoid presenting speculation as established reporting.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Our commitment</h2>
      <p>Articles should be clear about their evidence, link to useful sources when available, and be corrected when material facts change. The publication does not accept payment in exchange for favorable editorial coverage.</p>
    </section>

    <div class="infoActions">
      <a class="btn primary" href="/latest">Read the latest</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/method">See our method</a>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
